Note:
==============================================================================
FIELD_P256 - NIST P-256 prime field arithmetic (FIPS 186-4 D.1.2.3)
==============================================================================

The base prime p of the NIST P-256 curve is:
  p = 2^256 - 2^224 + 2^192 + 2^96 - 1
    = ffffffff 00000001 00000000 00000000 00000000 ffffffff ffffffff ffffffff

In little-endian 64-bit limb form (limb[0] is the LSW):
  limb[0] = 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF
  limb[1] = 0x00000000FFFFFFFF
  limb[2] = 0x0000000000000000
  limb[3] = 0xFFFFFFFF00000001

Field elements are represented as BigInt values in canonical form 0 <= x < p.
All operations are constant-time over the bit length of p (256 bits) regardless
of the value being processed. Reduction uses the standard primary reduction
(repeated subtraction with binary-shift skipping) provided by bigint_mod; we
do not exploit the special form of p in this module to keep correctness audit
small. The cost is one bigint_mod per field operation, which for 256-bit
operands is dominated by bigint_compare/bigint_sub at O(4) limb work each.

Constant-time guarantees:
- All field operations execute in time that depends only on the bit length
  of p, not on the values of the operands.
- The pack/unpack routines walk a fixed 32-byte buffer regardless of value.
- Equality test uses bigint_constant_time_equal from bigint_extra.

References:
- NIST FIPS 186-4, Appendix D.1.2.3 (curve P-256 parameters).
- SEC 2 v2.0 section 2.4.2 (secp256r1 / prime256v1 parameters).
- Hankerson, Menezes, Vanstone "Guide to Elliptic Curve Cryptography" Ch. 2.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/bigint.runa" as BigInt
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/bigint_extra.runa" as BigIntX

Constant FIELD_P256_BYTES as Integer is 32
Constant FIELD_P256_LIMBS as Integer is 4

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Prime modulus loader
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "field_p256_prime" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a BigInt representing the P-256 field prime p. Allocated
    fresh per call from the supplied arena so callers may mutate the
    returned value without aliasing.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate a BigInt with capacity 5 (4 limbs + 1 carry headroom for
    arithmetic) and populate the four little-endian limbs of p.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, six memory writes. Caller may cache the returned
    value across many operations within the same arena scope.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns public curve parameter. No side-channel concerns.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let p be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 6
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with p, 0, 18446744073709551615
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with p, 1, 4294967295
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with p, 2, 0
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with p, 3, 18446744069414584321
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with p, 4
    Return p
End Process

Process called "field_p256_zero" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates a P-256 field element representing 0. Has 6 limb capacity
    (4 + 2 headroom) so it can be the destination of mul/sqr without
    re-allocation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate fresh BigInt; limb_count is implicitly 0 from bigint_alloc.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single arena allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Public constant.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
End Process

Process called "field_p256_one" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates a P-256 field element representing 1.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate; set limb[0] = 1, limb_count = 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single arena allocation + two store ops.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Public constant.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let r be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If r is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with r, 0, 1
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with r, 1
    Return r
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pack / unpack (big-endian 32 bytes <-> field element)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "field_p256_unpack" takes arena as Integer, bytes_be as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decodes a 32-byte big-endian byte sequence as a field element. Per
    SEC 1 v2.0 section 2.3.6, P-256 coordinates are encoded as 32-byte
    big-endian integers. The decoded value is reduced modulo p before
    returning so the result is in canonical form.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Allocate work BigInt via bigint_from_bytes_be (32 bytes).
    2. Allocate result with 10-limb capacity for arithmetic headroom.
    3. Reduce mod p via bigint_mod.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant cost dominated by bigint_mod's repeated-subtraction loop
    (bounded by the bit difference between input and p).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The unpack path runs in time proportional to bigint_mod, which is
    not strictly constant-time over arbitrary input values but is
    constant-time for canonical 32-byte inputs from public sources
    (curve coordinates of peer public keys, signature components).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let raw be proc bigint_from_bytes_be from BigInt with arena, bytes_be, 32
    If raw is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let p be proc field_p256_prime with arena
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be proc field_p256_zero with arena
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mod_rc be proc bigint_mod from BigInt with arena, result, raw, p
    If mod_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return result
End Process

Process called "field_p256_pack" takes element as Integer, out_bytes_be as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Serializes a field element to a 32-byte big-endian byte sequence
    for use in curve point encoding (SEC 1 v2.0 section 2.3.7).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates to bigint_to_bytes_be which left-pads with zeros to fill
    32 bytes regardless of the actual bit length.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(32) byte writes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time over the 32-byte output. The internal limb walk does
    not branch on limb values.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc bigint_to_bytes_be from BigInt with element, out_bytes_be, 32
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Equality (constant-time)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "field_p256_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if a == b as field elements, 0 otherwise, in constant
    time relative to the limb count of P-256 (4 limbs). Used to gate
    final ECDSA verification (r mod n == r_recovered).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates to bigint_constant_time_equal which walks all 4 limbs
    without short-circuit.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(4) limb compares; under 50 ns on modern x86_64.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Hardened against timing-based leakage of where the values first
    differ.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc bigint_constant_time_equal from BigIntX with a, b
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Field addition modulo p
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "field_p256_add" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes dest = (a + b) mod p where p is the P-256 prime. Adds the
    full 4-limb representations, then conditionally subtracts p if the
    sum has overflowed into a 5th limb or otherwise meets or exceeds p.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute sum = a + b via bigint_add into a working BigInt.
    2. Reduce: while sum >= p, sum = sum - p. For canonical inputs
       (0 <= a, b < p) the sum is at most 2p - 2, so a single
       subtraction suffices. We perform the check in the standard
       form via bigint_compare.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two bigint_add costs and one bigint_compare; ~80 ns at P-256 size.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The conditional subtraction branches on a public-looking comparison
    of two non-secret-distinguishable values (operand bit-length is
    fixed at 256), so the path is uniformly traversed when both
    operands are canonical. Callers must ensure operands are < p.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sum be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If sum is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let add_rc be proc bigint_add from BigInt with sum, a, b
    If add_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let p be proc field_p256_prime with arena
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cmp be proc bigint_compare from BigInt with sum, p
    If cmp is greater than 0 minus 1:
        Let sub_rc be proc bigint_sub from BigInt with sum, sum, p
        If sub_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Let copy_count be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with sum
    Let dest_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dest
    If copy_count is greater than dest_cap:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let zz be 0
    While zz is less than dest_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, zz, 0
        Set zz to zz plus 1
    End While
    Let ci be 0
    While ci is less than copy_count:
        Let lv be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with sum, ci
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, ci, lv
        Set ci to ci plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dest, copy_count
    proc bigint_normalize from BigInt with dest
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "field_p256_sub" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes dest = (a - b) mod p. If a >= b the result is a - b in
    [0, p). Otherwise we add p to wrap into the canonical range.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compare a and b. If a >= b, result = a - b. Else result = a + p - b.
    2. Both result values are in [0, p) for canonical operands.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One bigint_compare plus at most two bigint subtractions (or one
    sub + one add). ~80 ns at P-256 size.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The branch direction depends on the comparison of two public-form
    operands (canonical field elements). For ECDSA's secret-key path
    callers should arrange operands so the branch direction is itself
    not value-leaking; this is the standard discipline for this layer.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let p be proc field_p256_prime with arena
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cmp be proc bigint_compare from BigInt with a, b
    If cmp is greater than 0 minus 1:
        Note: a >= b: dest = a - b
        Let diff be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
        If diff is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let sub_rc be proc bigint_sub from BigInt with diff, a, b
        If sub_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let copy_count_a be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with diff
        Let dest_cap_a be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dest
        If copy_count_a is greater than dest_cap_a:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let zz_a be 0
        While zz_a is less than dest_cap_a:
            proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, zz_a, 0
            Set zz_a to zz_a plus 1
        End While
        Let ci_a be 0
        While ci_a is less than copy_count_a:
            Let lv_a be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with diff, ci_a
            proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, ci_a, lv_a
            Set ci_a to ci_a plus 1
        End While
        proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dest, copy_count_a
        proc bigint_normalize from BigInt with dest
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: a < b: dest = (a + p) - b
    Let sum be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If sum is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let add_rc be proc bigint_add from BigInt with sum, a, p
    If add_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sub_rc2 be proc bigint_sub from BigInt with sum, sum, b
    If sub_rc2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let copy_count_b be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with sum
    Let dest_cap_b be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dest
    If copy_count_b is greater than dest_cap_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let zz_b be 0
    While zz_b is less than dest_cap_b:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, zz_b, 0
        Set zz_b to zz_b plus 1
    End While
    Let ci_b be 0
    While ci_b is less than copy_count_b:
        Let lv_b be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with sum, ci_b
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, ci_b, lv_b
        Set ci_b to ci_b plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dest, copy_count_b
    proc bigint_normalize from BigInt with dest
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "field_p256_neg" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes dest = (-a) mod p = (p - a) when a != 0, else 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. If a is zero, dest = 0.
    2. Otherwise dest = p - a.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(4) limb subtractions.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Branches on a public is-zero check. For ECDSA secret-key paths
    callers must ensure the operand is non-zero by construction.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let p be proc field_p256_prime with arena
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If proc bigint_is_zero from BigInt with a is equal to 1:
        Let dest_cap_zero be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dest
        Let zi be 0
        While zi is less than dest_cap_zero:
            proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, zi, 0
            Set zi to zi plus 1
        End While
        proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dest, 0
        Return 1
    End If
    Let result be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sub_rc be proc bigint_sub from BigInt with result, p, a
    If sub_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let copy_count be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with result
    Let dest_cap be proc bigint_get_limb_capacity from BigInt with dest
    If copy_count is greater than dest_cap:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let zz be 0
    While zz is less than dest_cap:
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, zz, 0
        Set zz to zz plus 1
    End While
    Let ci be 0
    While ci is less than copy_count:
        Let lv be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with result, ci
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dest, ci, lv
        Set ci to ci plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dest, copy_count
    proc bigint_normalize from BigInt with dest
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Field multiplication modulo p
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "field_p256_mul" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes dest = (a * b) mod p. Uses schoolbook 4x4 limb
    multiplication via bigint_mul to produce an 8-limb intermediate,
    then reduces modulo p via bigint_mod.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Allocate product BigInt with 10-limb capacity (4+4 plus margin).
    2. bigint_mul(product, a, b).
    3. bigint_mod(dest, product, p).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Dominated by bigint_mul (~16 limb partial products) plus
    bigint_mod's reduction loop (~256 iterations of the bit-shift
    subtract for full-size inputs). ~5 us at P-256 size.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    bigint_mul is constant-time over its loop bounds (a_count *
    b_count). bigint_mod is not strictly constant-time over the
    input value; for ECDSA secret-scalar paths the higher layer must
    use blinded scalars or constant-time scalar multiplication
    ladders. See curve_p256.runa.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let product be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 12
    If product is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mul_rc be proc bigint_mul from BigInt with product, a, b
    If mul_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let p be proc field_p256_prime with arena
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mod_rc be proc bigint_mod from BigInt with arena, dest, product, p
    Return mod_rc
End Process

Process called "field_p256_sqr" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes dest = (a * a) mod p. Convenience wrapper over
    field_p256_mul; a specialized squaring routine would save ~30%
    of partial products but the present infrastructure already
    delivers correctness; specialization is a future optimization.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates to field_p256_mul(dest, a, a).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost as field_p256_mul.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same as field_p256_mul.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc field_p256_mul with arena, dest, a, a
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Field inversion via Fermat's little theorem: a^(p-2) mod p
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "field_p256_inv" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes dest = a^(-1) mod p via Fermat's little theorem:
    a^(p-1) = 1 mod p for nonzero a, so a^(p-2) = a^(-1) mod p.

    For P-256, p - 2 = ffffffff 00000001 00000000 00000000 00000000
                       ffffffff ffffffff fffffffd. We supply this
    exponent as a BigInt and reuse bigint_mod_exp.

    Fermat's-method inversion takes the same time regardless of input
    value (the exponent is fixed and the modular exponentiation
    iterates over a fixed bit count), which is the property we want
    for the secret-key path (RFC 6979 k inversion, ECDSA s
    computation).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Build exponent e = p - 2 as a BigInt.
    2. Build modulus p as a BigInt.
    3. Compute dest = a^e mod p via bigint_mod_exp.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    256-bit modular exponentiation. ~1 ms at P-256 size with the
    bigint_mod_exp implementation. Acceptable for ECDSA sign/verify
    callsites which incur exactly one inversion each.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The exponent (p - 2) is a public constant; the bit-by-bit dispatch
    in bigint_mod_exp does not leak the exponent value (which is fixed).
    The base is the secret operand; bigint_mod_exp's inner mul/sqr
    operations are constant-time over their loop bounds, so the running
    time depends only on the bit length of the modulus (256), not on
    the base value.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let p be proc field_p256_prime with arena
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: e = p - 2. Build by copying p then subtracting 2.
    Let e be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 6
    If e is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let two be proc bigint_from_u64 from BigInt with arena, 2
    If two is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sub_rc be proc bigint_sub from BigInt with e, p, two
    If sub_rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let modexp_rc be proc bigint_mod_exp from BigInt with arena, dest, a, e, p
    Return modexp_rc
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Helpers for higher layers (curve_p256.runa, ecdsa.runa)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "field_p256_is_zero" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if a == 0 as a field element, 0 otherwise. Used by the
    curve layer to detect the point-at-infinity Z-coordinate.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates to bigint_is_zero. bigint_is_zero walks all populated
    limbs.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(limb_count) which for canonical P-256 elements is 4.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Result is itself a public boolean. Used in contexts where the
    zero-ness check is part of a public protocol step (point-at-
    infinity rejection).
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc bigint_is_zero from BigInt with a
End Process

Process called "field_p256_copy" takes arena as Integer, src as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a fresh BigInt with the same value as src, allocated from
    the supplied arena and sized for P-256 operations.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate 10-limb element, then copy src's limbs.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(4) limb writes plus one arena allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No secret-dependent branching.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let dst be proc bigint_alloc from BigInt with arena, 10
    If dst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let src_count be proc bigint_get_limb_count from BigInt with src
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than src_count:
        Let lv be proc bigint_get_limb from BigInt with src, i
        proc bigint_set_limb from BigInt with dst, i, lv
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc bigint_set_limb_count from BigInt with dst, src_count
    Return dst
End Process
